-- Philippine Stocks: DMCI, Holcim, IPVG, Philippine Telephone
-- B y   I a n   S a y s o n
-- 2012-01-02T07:47:40Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-01-02/alliance-manila-electric-megaworld-philippine-stocks-preview.html
Shares of the following companies had
 unusual (PCOMP)  moves in  Philippine (PASHR)  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the close Manila.  The  Philippine Stock Exchange Index (PCOMP)  rose 0.6 percent to
4,397.08, the highest since Aug. 18. The gauge rose for a third
straight year in 2011, adding 4.1 percent. The nation’s
financial markets were shut for a holiday on Dec. 30.  Infrastructure stocks:  Holcim Philippines Inc. (HLCM)  ,
the nation’s largest cement producer, advanced 5.3 percent to
9.90 pesos, the highest close since Sept. 1.  DMCI Holdings Inc. (DMC) 
, the nation’s biggest construction company, increased
2.7 percent to 42.40 pesos, the close since Aug. 16.  Southeast
Asia Cement Holdings Inc. (CMT)   advanced 5 percent to 1.68
pesos, the highest since April 18.  The government is ready to start 141.8 billion pesos ($3.23
billion) worth of public works projects this month, Secretary
Butch Abad said today.  IPVG Corp. (IP)   jumped 7.3 percent to 1.32 pesos, the
sharpest gain since Nov. 24. The company’s board authorized its
management to sign a guarantee agreement with Trade and
Investment Development Corp. for as much as 200 million pesos, a
stock-exchange filing showed.  Manila Electric Co. (MER)  , the largest Philippine
electricity retailer, climbed 3.2 percent to 255 pesos, the
highest close since Sept. 20. The company will probably meet its
14.5 billion-peso profit guidance in 2011, Chief Operating
Officer Oscar Reyes said.  Philippine Long Distance Telephone Co. (TEL)  , the
nation’s biggest phone company, advanced 1 percent to 2,568
pesos, the steepest gain since Dec. 20. Philippine Telephone
will complete an upgrade of its network one year ahead of
schedule, BusinessWorld reported, citing President Napoleon
Nazareno. Nazareno couldn’t be reached in his office for
comment.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Ian Sayson in  Manila  at 
 isayson@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
